Part II: The Post-9/11 Expansion - Capabilities Without Constraints
The reforms that followed the Church Committee were not reversed overnight. They were reversed over decades, accelerated sharply after September 11, 2001, and then quietly normalized. Understanding this requires examining not just what programs were created but what legal architecture was built around them.
The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001 dramatically expanded the government's authority to conduct surveillance on Americans with reduced judicial oversight. Section 215, which authorized collection of "any tangible things" relevant to a terrorism investigation, was used by the NSA - as revealed by Edward Snowden in 2013 - to justify bulk collection of the telephone metadata of virtually every American. This was not a narrow targeting of suspects. It was comprehensive population surveillance. The legal theory that permitted it - that collecting metadata does not constitute a "search" under the Fourth Amendment because the records belong to the telecommunications companies - was eventually rejected by courts, but the collection had already proceeded for years and the infrastructure remains.
PRISM, revealed in the same Snowden disclosures, gave the NSA direct access to the servers of major internet companies - Microsoft, Google, Apple, Facebook, Yahoo, and others - collecting emails, chat logs, video calls, photos, documents, and connection logs. The legal basis was Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act, which permits surveillance of foreign persons but in practice sweeps in enormous quantities of American communications through what the intelligence community calls "incidental collection." Section 702 was reauthorized in 2024 with expanded provisions, including the ability to compel a wider range of businesses to assist in surveillance - explicitly broadening, not narrowing, the scope.
The Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court, created in 1978 as a check on executive surveillance power, has become a structural fiction of judicial oversight. It operates in complete secrecy, hears only from government lawyers, has approved the overwhelming majority of surveillance warrants presented to it, and its targets have no knowledge they were surveilled and no mechanism to challenge the warrants. The existence of a court with only one party - the government - is not judicial oversight. It is judicial ceremony in service of executive authority.
The Authorization for Use of Military Force, passed in the week following September 11, 2001, was written in seventy-two hours and has never been repealed. It has been used to justify military operations in at least nineteen countries. It has been invoked to justify drone assassinations of American citizens abroad without trial - a practice the Obama administration defended in a classified legal memorandum. The precedent that the executive may kill an American citizen without judicial process, on the basis of a classified determination that the person is an enemy combatant, exists as established policy. The extension of that logic to domestic covert operations against Americans who are not killed but are surveilled, infiltrated, and destabilized is not a large step.
The Department of Homeland Security's fusion centers - over eighty across the country - were created to share intelligence between federal, state, and local law enforcement. Senate investigations found that many produced "predominantly useless information" but also generated intelligence reports on constitutionally protected activities: Occupy Wall Street organizing, Black Lives Matter protests, Standing Rock pipeline protests, and Muslim community gatherings. The Standing Rock case is particularly instructive. Internal documents obtained by The Intercept revealed that a private security firm working for the Dakota Access Pipeline - TigerSwan - coordinated directly with law enforcement, treated protesters as an "insurgency," and employed tactics drawn from counterinsurgency doctrine developed in Iraq and Afghanistan. The pipeline company, Energy Transfer Partners, contracted TigerSwan without state licensing. TigerSwan used aerial surveillance, infiltration, and intelligence-sharing with law enforcement against American citizens engaged in constitutionally protected protest. This is precisely the privatization of covert enforcement that an adapted American Gestapo would require to maintain official deniability.

