Part V: Privatization and the Contractor Network
The most significant structural adaptation of any American covert enforcement apparatus to the US constitutional context would be the privatization of its most sensitive operations through private contractors, who operate largely outside the oversight mechanisms that nominally constrain government agencies.
This is not hypothetical. It is the documented structure of the post-9/11 intelligence expansion. Following September 11, the intelligence community underwent the largest expansion in its history. A significant portion of that expansion was through contractors. By 2013, approximately 70% of the US intelligence budget - roughly $52 billion annually - was spent on private contractors. Edward Snowden, who revealed the NSA's bulk surveillance programs, was himself a contractor employee of Booz Allen Hamilton. The private contractor infrastructure for intelligence and covert operations is enormous, deeply embedded, and subject to substantially less oversight than government agencies.
The implications extend beyond intelligence to covert domestic operations. Private contractors operating at government direction, or in coordination with government agencies, can conduct activities that the government cannot officially authorize without triggering legal constraints. This is the structure that appeared at Standing Rock - private security firms conducting counterinsurgency operations against American citizens at the direction of corporate clients who coordinated with government law enforcement. The government maintains plausible deniability. The private firms operate in legal gray zones. The targets have no clear constitutional remedy.
The Church Committee's reforms were designed to constrain government agencies. They were not designed to constrain the contractor networks that did not yet exist at scale. The privatization of covert operations is therefore not just an operational convenience but a structural workaround for the specific legal constraints that the post-COINTELPRO reforms imposed.

