Part VI: What the Evidence Does Not Establish - The Honest Accounting
Intellectual honesty requires stating clearly what this essay has not proven and what the available evidence does not support.
The documented case for a systematic, centrally-directed program of assassination of domestic political dissidents is not made. COINTELPRO's collaboration in the killing of Fred Hampton is documented. Whether such programs continue at scale is not established by available evidence. The "What Does Not Parallel" section of the document under discussion is correct that extrajudicial killing of domestic dissidents is not a documented feature of the current apparatus.
The documented case for secret domestic prisons holding American citizens is not made. Guantánamo holds non-citizens under genuinely extraordinary legal circumstances. There is no equivalent documented for American citizens on American soil.
The documented case for a fully controlled judiciary is not made. Courts have repeatedly ruled against executive overreach, and those rulings have generally been obeyed. The judiciary is under pressure and operates within constraints - the FISA court is a genuine pathology - but it retains substantial independence.
The individual experiences of people who describe being targeted by "directed energy weapons," organized stalking by strangers, or coordinated psychological harassment through street theater are genuinely difficult to assess. The pattern of experiences described by some self-identified "targeted individuals" is consistent with documented COINTELPRO tactics - particularly the psychological harassment components - and also consistent with certain psychiatric conditions. The honest assessment is that these experiences cannot be evaluated individually as proof of a systematic program, even while the historical record establishes that systematic programs producing similar experiences have existed.
These limitations are why the probability is 70% and not 90%. The countervailing institutions - the judiciary, investigative journalism, civil liberties organizations, occasional congressional investigations - are real and functioning, if imperfect and under pressure. They are genuine constraints on the scope and severity of any covert enforcement apparatus.

