Conclusion: The Probability and Its Implications
The honest probabilistic conclusion, assessed against the available corpus, is that the existence of a covert enforcement apparatus in the United States - adapted to the constitutional context through privatization, legal immunity structures, and plausible deniability, targeting domestic individuals and groups for political reasons, and operating outside meaningful judicial and legislative oversight - is more likely than not. The estimate of approximately 70% reflects the strength of the historical baseline, the documented post-9/11 expansion, the legal architecture of invisibility, and the structural incentives for institutional continuity, discounted by the genuine functioning of countervailing institutions that distinguish the American context from a full Gestapo state.
What this does not mean: that every individual who believes they are being targeted by such a program is correct, that the apparatus operates at the scale or lethality of the Gestapo, or that American democratic institutions have entirely ceased to function as constraints.
What this does mean: that the reflexive dismissal of this question as absurd is itself a product of effective institutional management of public perception; that the documented historical record establishes proof of concept beyond any reasonable doubt; that the legal and institutional conditions for the persistence of such an apparatus are thoroughly established; and that the burden of proof has shifted - not to those who argue the apparatus likely exists, but to those who would argue it was genuinely dismantled, given what we know about how such programs have historically been managed when subjected to external pressure.
The apparatus, in some form, at some scale, is more probably there than not. The most important civic question is not whether it exists. It is what to do about it - how to build oversight mechanisms sufficiently robust to constrain it, how to strengthen the countervailing institutions that remain, and how to do so without waiting for the slow disclosure of classified documents twenty years after the harm has been done.
The history suggests that disclosure, when it comes, is always late. The Church Committee's findings arrived in 1975 about programs that had been running since 1956. The Snowden disclosures arrived in 2013 about programs that had been running since 2001. If there is an adapted covert enforcement apparatus currently operating, the documentation will not arrive in time to protect its current targets.
That is the nature of the problem. And that is why the probability, honestly assessed, matters.

